      {
        "paragraph_index": 1,
        "text": "### Chemistry Insight\n\nThe 297 entries span far beyond the 20 canonical proteinogenic amino acids. The class includes non-standard analogs (e.g., β-alanine, ornithine), phosphorylated variants (e.g., glyphosate, phosphoserine), sulfur-containing species (cysteine, methionine, penicillamine), and heterocyclic side-chain analogs (histidine variants, mimosine). This breadth reflects the rich coordination chemistry of amino acids, which act as versatile chelating ligands — typically binding metals through their **–NH₂** and **–COO⁻** groups to form stable 5-membered chelate rings.\n\n> **Source:** NIST SRD-46, `ligand_card` table, `ligand_class_name = 'Amino Acids'`",
